result.execSummary:
The defendant Amber L. Parsons was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Sentence is imposed and stayed, if imposed defendant is granted huber privileges and 60 days to pay any outstanding financial obligations as ordered by the Court.
Concurrent with: Stayed sentence in case 14CM223 Ct 1 and Ct 2.

Defendant was ordered to report immediately to the probation and parole office.
Concurrent with: Probation on Ct 1 and Ct 2 in case 14CM223.

miscConds.notes: Defendant is to seek employment or be in school if agent finds this to be appropriate.

Defendant shall attend counseling, treatments, programming, evaluations as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request  Defendant is to undergo a psychological evaluation and follow all recommendations, releasing records to the agent.

Defendant shall not possess or consume any medication or drug except as may be specifically prescribed by a medical professional for defendant, and then shall be taken only as prescribed.  Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, and not go into places that sell alcohol except incidentally such as a grocery store, convenience store or gas station or other such place where alcohol is not sold for consumption on the premises. 
AMENDED  03/15/2018  Exception:  Defendant may be in places where alcohol is served or sold, within the scope of her employment and with the the approval of her probation agent.  
Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety.    The defendant shall have no contact with Thomas Mortenson or Renee Mortenson  of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way unless she has consent of the agent and the people. 
The defendant is not to own, possess, be in charge of, or be alone with any animal without the consent of her agent, and she must allow the agent into her home to see that she is complying with this order
The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent.  The defendant shall submit to random urine/PBT testing as required by the agent or any law enforcement officer.
